Predicting groups: Logistic Regression

Logistic regression is a method of predicting predefined group classification using one or more predictor variables. It is similar to DFA, but is more robust to violations of normality and the models are easier to interpret. Additionally, categorical variables can be used as predictors in logistic regression (but not in DFA)

Assumptions:

  1. Multivariate normality (i.e., the predictor variables are normal for each group) - but logistic regression is robust to violations here
  2. Homogeneity of variance
  3. There must be at least as many cases as predictors. A more conservative case is to have approximately 15 cases per predictor.
  4. If multiple predictor variables are used, variables must not be collinear.

Data

In this tutorial, we will be looking at essays written by individuals at three different levels of lexical proficiency (Beginner, Intermediate, and High). We will also be looking at the average meaningfulness score for all words in each text. Meaningfulness scores are one way of determining how many concepts a particular word might be related to (e.g., the word “food” would be more “meaningful” than “zygote” because it could be used in more semantic contexts). We will be using meaningfulness scores to predict the lexical proficiency of each essay.

Conducting the analysis

Training and test sets

To ensure the generalizability of our results, we will divide our data into a training set and a test set. The model will be created using the training set, and then will be applied to the test set in order to determine how well the model works on new data. A variety of splits can be used, but the most common is to use 67% of the data for the training set and 33% for the test set. In larger data sets, we might change that to a 90/10 split, and in a smaller data set, it might get changed to a 50/50 split. With an increase in training data, our model gets better. But, as our test set becomes smaller, it is less representative, and therefore might provide inaccurate results.

library(MASS)
## 
## Attaching package: 'MASS'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     select
set.seed(1) #this will ensure that our random sample won't change each time we run the analysis
training_sample <- sample(c(TRUE, FALSE), nrow(mydata), replace = T, prob = c(0.67,0.33))
train <- mydata[training_sample, ] #this creates the training set
test <- mydata[!training_sample, ] #this creates the test set

Building model

To build the logistic regression model, we will use the multinom() function in the nnet package.

library(nnet)
#first, we set a reference level for our categorical data:
train$Proficiency <-relevel(train$Proficiency, ref = "Beginner")
#then, we build the model
lr1 <- multinom(Proficiency ~ Meaningfulness_AW , data = train)
## # weights:  9 (4 variable)
## initial  value 180.172415 
## iter  10 value 154.011669
## iter  20 value 152.960778
## final  value 152.952109 
## converged
summary(lr1)
## Call:
## multinom(formula = Proficiency ~ Meaningfulness_AW, data = train)
## 
## Coefficients:
##      (Intercept) Meaningfulness_AW
## High    30.39833       -0.08113951
## Int     12.14724       -0.02985717
## 
## Std. Errors:
##       (Intercept) Meaningfulness_AW
## High 1.772633e-06      0.0006573507
## Int  1.319143e-06      0.0005153214
## 
## Residual Deviance: 305.9042 
## AIC: 313.9042
#to get p values, we have to do a little more work
#first, we convert our data to z values:
z_lr1 <- summary(lr1)$coefficients / summary(lr1)$standard.errors

#then, we get the two-tailed p-value
pnorm(abs(z_lr1), lower.tail=FALSE)*2
##      (Intercept) Meaningfulness_AW
## High           0                 0
## Int            0                 0

In this case, both our intercept and our predictor variable have a p-value that approaches 0

#this will give the probability that each observation should belong to each class
predicted_train <- predict(lr1,train,"probs")

#this is how we obtain the predicted values 
predicted_class_train <- predict(lr1,train)

#this is our confusion matrix
cf1 <- table(predicted_class_train,train$Proficiency)
print(cf1)
##                      
## predicted_class_train Beginner High Int
##              Beginner        6    0   4
##              High            0    7  11
##              Int            34   32  70

Now, we can check the prediction accuracy more formally:

n = sum(cf1) #number of essays
diag1 = diag(cf1) # number of correctly classified instances per class 
macro_acc = sum(diag1)/n #macro accuracy
print(macro_acc)
## [1] 0.5060976

As we can see, our macro average for the training set is similar (but slightly lower) to our macro results for the DFA model in the previous tutorial.

We will now run a full work up on the prediction accuracy. To save ourselves some time later, we will create a function (called “prediction_stats()”), which will give us the stats for our confusion matrix.

#The below stats are needed to calculate precision, recall, and F1
prediction_stats <- function(table1) {
n = sum(table1) #number of essays
nc = nrow(table1) # number of classes
diag1 = diag(table1) # number of correctly classified instances per class 
rowsums = apply(table1, 1, sum) # number of instances per class
colsums = apply(table1, 2, sum) # number of predictions per class
p = rowsums / n # distribution of instances over the actual classes
q = colsums / n # distribution of instances over the predicted classes

 precision = diag1 / colsums 
 recall = diag1 / rowsums 
 f1 = 2 * precision * recall / (precision + recall) 
 
 return(data.frame(precision, recall, f1))
}

prediction_stats(cf1)
##          precision    recall        f1
## Beginner 0.1500000 0.6000000 0.2400000
## High     0.1794872 0.3888889 0.2456140
## Int      0.8235294 0.5147059 0.6334842

These results indicate that although the macro average was slightly lower than the DFA model in the previous tutorial, the logistic regression model is a bit better at predicting the High group (and slightly less at predicting the INT group).

Clearly, these results are not great. What can we do to improve our model accuracy? Two options are to a) add more predictor variables and/or b) find better predictor variables. We will do this below.

Using more than one predictor variable in a logistic regression.

In order to increase the prediction accuracy of our model, we are going to add another predictor variable (L1_Word_Reaction_Time). First, we need to check the assumptions for that variable AND ensure that it isn’t collinear with Meaningfulness_AW.

library("ggpubr")
ggdensity(mydata, x = "L1_Word_Reaction_Time",
          add = "mean", rug = TRUE,
          color = "Proficiency", fill = "Proficiency")

The density plot suggest that the data is roughly normal and have roughly equal variance (though clearly the high group has somewhat less variance than the other two groups). At any rate, for this tutorial, we will proceed with the analysis.

Next, we check to determine whether our two predictor variables are collinear. They do not reach a threshold of r = .700 (a fairly conservative threshold), so we can use both variables in the same model.

cor(mydata$Meaningfulness_AW,mydata$L1_Word_Reaction_Time)
## [1] -0.447012

Now, we build the model using both predictor variables and get the p-values

#then, we build the model
lr2 <- multinom(Proficiency ~ Meaningfulness_AW + L1_Word_Reaction_Time , data = train)
